        "content": "<p>The simplest situation is enough:<br>\nf and g are real functions that are continuous on [a,b]</p>",
        "id": 515269401,
        "sender_full_name": "Jiatong Yang",
        "timestamp": 1746010295
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"478392\">Jiatong Yang</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/217875-Is-there-code-for-X.3F/topic/Cauchy.20Schwarz.20inequality.20integral.20form/near/515269401\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>The simplest situation is enough:<br>\nf and g are real functions that are continuous on [a,b]</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Mathlib is very general, so the CS inequality will be phrased in terms of an inner product space. Perhaps <br>\n<a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Analysis/InnerProductSpace/Basic.html#real_inner_mul_inner_self_le\">https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Analysis/InnerProductSpace/Basic.html#real_inner_mul_inner_self_le</a></p>\n<p>Is a start, you will also need to have that Inner Product instance(the one that does the integral)</p>\n<p>I think there is a Holder inequality using integral notation though, integral_mul_norm_le_Lp_mul_Lq could help</p>",
        "id": 515273126,
        "sender_full_name": "Yan Yablonovskiy",
        "timestamp": 1746011331
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Indeed a combination of <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=norm_inner_le_norm#doc\">docs#norm_inner_le_norm</a> and <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=MeasureTheory.L2.innerProductSpace#doc\">docs#MeasureTheory.L2.innerProductSpace</a> essentially give the correct version of Cauchy-Schwarz for integrals. (In your example case of continuous functions on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mi>a</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>b</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">[a,b]</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">a</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">b</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span></span></span></span>, <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=BoundedContinuousFunction.mem_Lp#doc\">docs#BoundedContinuousFunction.mem_Lp</a> with the finite measure given by the restriction of the Lebesgue measure on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mi>a</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>b</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">[a,b]</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">a</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">b</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span></span></span></span> gives the <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>L</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">L^2</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>-membership.) Note, however, that the inequality you stated in the original question is not true; the squares on the RHS should be on the functions inside the integrals, not on the integrals.</p>",
        "id": 515274465,
        "sender_full_name": "Kalle Kytölä",
        "timestamp": 1746011749
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=MeasureTheory.integral_mul_norm_le_Lp_mul_Lq#doc\">docs#MeasureTheory.integral_mul_norm_le_Lp_mul_Lq</a> could also help, depending on what you need integral CS for.</p>",
